The '''Congress of South African Writers''' (COSAW) is a [[South African]] grassroots writer’s organisation.
Launched in July 1987,<ref>{{cite news | last = Kraft | first = Scott | coauthors = | title = Perceptive Works Earned Respect of S. African Blacks Nobel: Nadine Gordimer's opposition to apartheid, evident in her books, also took her to court. | work = Los Angeles Times | pages = 13 | language = | publisher = | date = 1991-10-04 | url = https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/61506401.html?dids=61506401:61506401&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&date=Oct+04%2C+1991&author=SCOTT+KRAFT&pub=Los+Angeles+Times+(pre-1997+Fulltext)&desc=Perceptive+Works+Earned+Respect+of+S.+African+Blacks+Nobel%3A+Nadine+Gordimer's+opposition+to+apartheid%2C+evident+in+her+books%2C+also+took+her+to+court.&pqatl=google | accessdate = 2008-06-15}}</ref> its initial aims were to promote literature and redress the imbalances of [[apartheid]] education. It organises literary events, liaises with literacy organisations, conducts research, establishes writing groups, facilitates workshops for aspirant writers from disadvantaged communities and publishes materials.
