{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}} {{Infobox politician | image = | imagesize = | honorific-prefix = Mayor | name = Frank Oliver Fowler | honorific-suffix = | caption = | order = 29th [[List of mayors of Winnipeg|Mayor of Winnipeg]] | term_start = 20 June 1922<ref name=WpgMayors>{{cite web|url=http://www.winnipeg.ca/Services/CityLife/HistoryOfWinnipeg/MayorsPastPresent.stm |accessdate=2009-01-11 |title=City Government Mayors, Past and Present |publisher=City of Winnipeg |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081225130928/http://winnipeg.ca/Services/CityLife/HistoryOfWinnipeg/MayorsPastPresent.stm |archivedate=25 December 2008 |df=dmy }}</ref> | term_end = 1922 | predecessor = [[Edward Parnell (politician)|Edward Parnell]] | successor = [[Seymour Farmer]] | birth_date = {{birth date|1861|12|14|df=yes}} | birth_place = [[Wingham, Ontario|Wingham]], [[Canada West]]<ref name=MHS /> | death_date = {{death date and age|1945|2|18|1861|12|14|df=yes}} | death_place = unknown | office2 = Member of the [[Legislative Assembly of Manitoba]] for [[Brandon South]] | term_start2 = 1897 | term_end2 = 1903 |predecessor2 = [[Herbert Graham]] |successor2 = [[Alfred Carroll]] | constituency = | party = | alma_mater = | spouse = Elizabeth Nichol | profession = farmer | religion = | signature = | footnotes = }}
'''Frank Oliver Fowler''' (14 December 1861 – 18 February 1945)<ref name=MHS>{{cite web | title=Frank Oliver Fowler (1861-1945) | url=http://www.mhs.mb.ca/docs/people/fowler_fo.shtml | publisher=Manitoba Historical Society | date=19 October 2008 | accessdate=2009-01-09 }}</ref> was a Canadian politician serving as a member of the [[Legislative Assembly of Manitoba]], then in Winnipeg city politics as an alderman and subsequently as the 29th Mayor.
He moved from Ontario to the [[Brandon, Manitoba]] region in the early 1880s where he was a farmer. He established a grain company in [[Wawanesa, Manitoba|Wawanesa]] in 1891 and became a leader in regional grain industry associations after Fowler and his family moved to Winnipeg in 1902.
Fowler was acclaimed to the Manitoba legislature for the South Brandon riding following a by-election on 20 November 1897. He was re-elected in the 1899 general provincial election and remained in provincial office until 1903.<ref name=LAM>{{cite web | url=https://www.gov.mb.ca/legislature/members/mla_bio_deceased.html#F0 | title=MLA Biographies - Deceased | date=14 November 2008 | accessdate=2009-01-11 | publisher=[[Legislative Assembly of Manitoba]] }}</ref> After leaving provincial office, he became a city alderman in 1908 where he supported restrictions on [[trade union]]s. He was acclaimed Mayor on 20 June 1922, 11 days after [[Edward Parnell (politician)|Edward Parnell]] died in office. Fowler served as Mayor for the remainder of that year.<ref name=MHS />
His name is commemorated by Fowler Street in Winnipeg.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.mhs.mb.ca/docs/winnipegstreets/index.shtml#f | title=History in Winnipeg Street Names | publisher=Manitoba Historical Society | accessdate=2009-01-11 | date=23 November 2008 }}</ref>
