{{Infobox member of the Knesset |image = |birth_date = 1 June 1937 |birth_place = [[Jatt, Israel|Jatt]], [[Mandatory Palestine]] |death_date = {{Death date and age|1994|9|24|1937|6|1|df=y}} |death_place = |Knesset(s) = [[Israeli legislative election, 1981|10]], [[Israeli legislative election, 1984|11]] |party1 = [[Alignment (political party)|Alignment]] |partyyears1 = 1981–1984 |party2 = [[Mapam]] |partyyears2 = 1984–1988 |party3 = [[Hadash]] |partyyears3 = 1988 |minister1 = }}
'''Muhammed Wattad''' ({{lang-ar|محمد وتد}}, {{lang-he|מוחמד ותד}}; 1 June 1937 – 24 September 1994) was an [[Israeli Arab]] journalist, writer and politician who served as a member of the [[Knesset]] between 1981 and 1988.
==Biography== Born in [[Jatt, Israel|Jatt]] during the [[Mandatory Palestine|Mandate era]], Wattad was a member of the Israeli Communist Youth and [[Hashomer Hatzair]]. He attended [[Tel Aviv University]], where he took Asian and African Studies.
A member of [[Mapam]], he edited the Arabic-language version of the party's newspaper, ''[[Al HaMishmar]]''. In [[Israeli legislative election, 1981|1981]] he was elected to the Knesset on the [[Alignment (political party)|Alignment]] list (an alliance of Mapam and the [[Israeli Labor Party|Labor Party]]). He was re-elected in [[Israeli legislative election, 1984|1984]], shortly after which Mapam left the Alignment. On 12 July 1988 he left Mapam to join Hadash,<ref>[https://www.knesset.gov.il/faction/eng/FactionHistoryAll_eng.asp Mergers and Splits amongst Parliamentary Groups] Knesset website</ref> due to disappointment with Mapam's policy towards the [[First Intifada]].
He lost his seat in the [[Israeli legislative election, 1988|1988 elections]]. After leaving politics, he managed and edited the ''[[Kul al-Arab]]'' newspaper, and later ran a public relations firm.
He died in 1994 following a traffic collision.
