'''Naim Ibrahim Attallah''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CBE}} ({{lang-ar|نعيم إبراهيم عطالله}}, born 1 May 1931) is a [[businessman]] and writer. He is the [[publisher]] of Quartet Books and the former owner of the Women's Press. The [[Palestine (region)|Palestinian]]-born entrepreneur was described by ''[[The Guardian]]'' in 2000 as a "legendary adorer of beautiful women".<ref>{{cite web|title=The Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/g2/story/0,3604,403383,00.html|accessdate=15 November 2016}}</ref>

He was born in the former [[Mandatory Palestine|British Mandate of Palestine]] in 1931. He is the publisher of Quartet Books, which was founded in 1972 by Ken Banerji, John Boothe, William Miller and Brian Thompson, and taken over by Attallah in 1976.<ref>[http://quartetbooks.co.uk/about "About"], Quartet Books website.</ref> Attallah is a former backer of the ''[[Literary Review]]'' and ''[[The Oldie]]''.<ref>[https://www.standard.co.uk/news/londoners-diary/oldie-celebrates-and-recognises-its-debt-to-naim-7906036.html "Oldie celebrates and recognises its debt to Naim"], ''[[Evening Standard]]'' — Diary, 3 July 2012.</ref> He is also the former owner of the London-based Women's Press,<ref>Miranda Seymour, [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/3664848/But-did-the-Medicis-have-as-much-fun.html# "But did the Medicis have as much fun?"], ''The Telegraph'', 3 May 2007.</ref> founded in 1977.<ref>[http://www.bookblast.com/popups/mediareleases/attallahmemoir1.pdf BookBlast PR, Media Release.]</ref>

His most recent book of memoirs, ''Fulfilment and Betrayal: 1975-1995'', was published in 2007.<ref>Terence Blacker, [http://terenceblacker.com/comment/from-the-independent/lewd-but-likeable-the-key-to-naim-attallah/ "Lewd but likeable: the key to Naim Attallah"]. From ''The Independent'', 2 May 2007.</ref>  According to [[Jennie Erdal]]'s memoir ''Ghosting'' (2005),<ref>{{cite book|last=Erdal|first=Jennie|authorlink=Jennie Erdal|title=Ghosting: A Memoir|year=2004|publisher=[[Canongate Books]]|isbn=1841955620}}</ref> she was the ghostwriter of some of his books, articles and other writings.<ref>Susan Salter Reynolds, [http://articles.latimes.com/2005/may/22/entertainment/ca-erdal22 "A former ghost takes to the light"], ''Los Angeles Times'', 22 May 2005.</ref>

Attallah was appointed [[Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] (CBE) in the [[2017 New Year Honours]] for services to literature and the arts.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=61803|supp=y|page=N8|date=31 December 2016}}</ref>

