{{Infobox Singapore neighbourhood |image = Singapore Skyline at Night with Black Sky.JPG |englishname = Raffles Place |chinesename = 莱佛士坊 |poj = |pengim = |pinyin = Láifóshì Fāng |malayname = Pesara Raffles |tamilname = ராஃபிள்ஸ் பிளேஸ் }}
'''Raffles Place''' is the centre of the Financial District of [[Singapore]] and is located south of the [[River|mouth]] of the [[Singapore River]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.roughguides.com/destinations/asia/singapore/financial-district/ |title= The Financial District |work=Rough Guide}}</ref> It was first planned and developed in the 1820s as '''Commercial Square''' to serve as the hub of the commercial zone of Singapore in [[Jackson Plan|Raffles Town Plan]]. It was renamed Raffles Place in 1858 and is now the site of a number of major banks. It is located in the [[Downtown Core]] within the [[Central Area, Singapore|Central Area]], and features some of the tallest buildings and landmarks of the country.
==History== [[File:Raffles Place.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.2|Centre square of Raffles Place]]
===Beginning=== The founder of modern Singapore, [[Sir Stamford Raffles]], intended Singapore to become a "great commercial [[Marketplace|emporium]]". As part of his plan, he gave instructions in 1822 that a commercial area be created on the southwest side of the Singapore River.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://archive.org/stream/ananecdotalhist00buckgoog#page/n114/mode/2up |title=An anecdotal history of old times in Singapore |author=Charles Burton Buckley |pages=81–86 |date=1902}}</ref> The Garrison Engineer [[Lieutenant]] R.N. [[Philip Jackson (surveyor)|Philip Jackson]], was tasked with drawing up a [[Jackson Plan|Town Plan]] based on Raffles' instructions. This commercial area was centered on Commercial Square, and was developed from 1823 to 1824.
A [[hill]] originally stood at the area between Commercial Square and Battery Road.<ref name="infopedia">{{cite web |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_864_2004-12-30.html |title=Raffles Place |work=Singapore Infopedia |publisher=National Library Board |first=Vernon |last=Cornelius}}</ref> Under Raffles' supervision, the hill was leveled, the soil of which was then used to reclaim the marshy southern bank of the Singapore River to form the [[Boat Quay]] and Circular Road area. Commercial Square was created as an open space 200 yards long by 50 yards wide, with a small garden in the middle.<ref name="anecdotal">{{cite book |url=https://archive.org/stream/ananecdotalhist00buckgoog#page/n120/mode/2up |title=An anecdotal history of old times in Singapore |author=Charles Burton Buckley |pages=88–89 |date=1902}}</ref> Lots of land in the area around the square were sold in auction at $1,200 and $1,500 apiece.<ref name="anecdotal"/> Commercial enterprises then became established on the area; two- and four-[[storey]] buildings were built around the square, housing [[mercantile]] offices, [[bank]]s and [[Trader (finance)|trading]] companies.<ref name="100 historic places"/>
On 8 March 1858, Commercial Square was renamed Raffles Place in Raffles' honour.<ref name="infopedia"/> On the south side of the square were many [[warehouse|godowns]] with [[jetties]] that allowed [[cargo]] to be loaded and unloaded directly from [[boat]]s as they were then located at the edge of the sea. From 1858 to 1864, the land on the south side of Raffles Place from [[Johnston's Pier]] to [[Telok Ayer Market]] was reclaimed, which became [[Collyer Quay]], named after the Chief Engineer George Collyer who initiated its construction.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_218_2005-01-19.html |title=Collyer Quay | first=Vernon |last=Cornelius |work=Singapore Infopedia |publisher=National Library Board }}</ref> The expansion freed up a larger area designated for commerce, and attracted more businesses such as [[retail]] stores and banks.<ref name="100 historic places">{{cite book |work=[[National Heritage Board (Singapore)|National Heritage Board]]|date=2002|title=Singapore's 100 Historic Places|publisher= Archipelago Press|isbn= 981-4068-23-3 |pages=44–45}}</ref>
===Commerce and retail === [[File:KITLV - 79891 - Kleingrothe, C.J. - Medan - Raffles Place, Singapore - circa 1910.tif|thumb|upright=1.2|Raffles Place {{circa}}1910]] The area become the location for well-known retail stores in the 19th century. A retail store that would become Singapore's oldest [[department store]] [[John Little (department store)|John Little]] was established on 30 August 1842 on Commercial Square.<ref name="st">{{cite news |url= http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/john-little-to-close-final-outlet-at-plaza-singapura-174-years-of-history-at-a-glance |title=John Little to close final outlet at Plaza Singapura: 174 years of history at a glance |first=Annabeth|last= Leow |work=The Straits Times |date=7 November 2016 }}</ref> [[Robinson & Co.|Robinsons]], another of the early department stores, was first established on Raffles Place in 1858 as a "family warehouse". Robinson's was then relocated elsewhere a few times before returning to Raffles Place in 1891.<ref name="robinsons">{{cite web |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_561_2005-01-25.html |title=Robinsons Department Store |work=Singapore Infopedia |publisher=National Library Board}}</ref> Whiteaway Laidlaw was first established on D'Almeida Street in 1900 before moving to [[Stamford House, Singapore|Stamford House]], then to Battery Road in 1910.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_1122_2006-06-15.html |title=Whiteaway Laidlaw |author=Joshua Chia Yeong Jia |work=Singapore Infopedia |publisher=National Library Board}}</ref> The Alkaff Arcade, Singapore's first indoor shopping arcade that stretched from the waterfront of [[Collyer Quay]] to Raffles Place, was built in 1909.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_1067_2006-06-15.html |title=The (Alkaff) Arcade |work=Singapore Infopedia |publisher=National Library Board |author=Marsita Omar}}</ref> A Chinese store, the Oriental Emporium, was opened opposite Robinsons in 1966.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://remembersingapore.org/2012/04/09/the-emporium-legend-lim-tow-yong/ |title=The Emporium Legend Lim Tow Yong (1925-2012)|date=9 April 2012 |work=Remember Singapore}}</ref>
[[File:Raffles Place Skyscrapers 4, Jan 06.JPG|thumb|upright|left|Three of the [[List of tallest buildings in Singapore|tallest buildings in Singapore]], located at Raffles Place, from left to right, [[Republic Plaza, Singapore|Republic Plaza]], [[UOB Plaza|UOB Plaza One]] and [[One Raffles Place]]. All three are 280 metres in height.]] The earliest banks to operate in Commercial Square were the [[Oriental Bank Corporation|Oriental Bank]], the Chartered [[Mercantile Bank of India, London and China]] (later absorbed into [[HSBC]]), the [[Chartered Bank of India, Australia and China]] (which later became the [[Standard Chartered]]), and the [[Asiatic Banking Corporation]].<ref name="infopedia"/> At the turn of the 20th century, the banking industry in Singapore took off. Home-grown banks came into play, competing against bigger banks with lower [[interest rate]]s and a [[cultural]] affinity with their customers. From the 1950s, banking in Singapore entered a new league, with [[Bank of America]] establishing itself here in 1955 at 31 Raffles Place, and [[Bank of China]] at the adjacent [[Battery Road]].<ref name="100 historic places"/>
During [[World War II]], Raffles Place was among the places hit by bombs when seventeen Japanese bombers conducted the [[Bombing of Singapore (8 December 1941)|first air raid on Singapore]] on 8 December 1941, during the [[Battle of Malaya]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_7_2005-01-25.html |title=First air raid on Singapore | first=Alvin |last=Chua|work=Singapore Infopedia |publisher=National Library Board }}</ref> The [[Japanese occupation of Singapore]] temporarily halted the near-continuous commercial development of Raffles Place.<ref name="100 historic places"/>
===Financial hub===
In the 1960s and 1970s, retailers began to moved away from Raffles Place area to locations such as High Street, [[North Bridge Road]] and [[Orchard Road]], and were replaced by [[finance]] houses and major banks. The Whiteaway Laidlaw department store building on Battery Road was taken over by [[Maybank|Malayan Bank]] in 1962, and then demolished to make way for the [[Maybank Tower (Singapore)|Maybank Tower]] in 1998.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_1122_2006-06-15.html|title=Whiteaway Laidlaw |author=Joshua Chia Yeong Jia |work=Singapore Infopedia |publisher=National Library Board }}</ref> Robinsons moved to Orchard Road after its landmark building was destroyed in one of the worst fires in Singapore's history in 1972, and its neighbour [[Overseas Union Bank]] expanded into the site with the construction of a new tower in 1986.<ref name="robinsons"/><ref name="infopedia"/> The John Little's Building was sold in 1973 and demolished.<ref name="st"/> [[File:Raffles Place Sculpture 2, Dec 05.JPG|thumb|upright|Modern-day Raffles Place, the financial heart of Singapore.]] The first underground car park in Singapore was constructed in 1965 under Raffles Place, but was replaced in the 1980s by the [[Raffles Place MRT Station]], which opened in December 1987.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://remembersingapore.org/2014/07/28/old-and-new-raffles-place/ |title=Raffles Place, 50 Years of Transformation |date= 28 July 2014 |work=Remember Singapore}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://remembersingapore.org/2013/07/23/singapore-mrt-history/ |title= A Journey into Singapore MRT’s Past |date= 23 July 2013 |work=Remember Singapore}}</ref> Its entrance features detailings of the facade of 1911 of the old John Little building.<ref name="infopedia"/>
Raffles Place is now dominated by [[Skyscraper]]s, some of the [[List of tallest buildings in Singapore|tallest buildings in Singapore]], which are the locations of flagship banks. [[United Overseas Bank]] tower was completed in 1974 on the old Bonham Building site, later renovated and expanded into [[UOB Plaza]]. Other towers such as [[Singapore Land Tower]], [[Clifford Centre]], Ocean Building, [[OUB Centre]], and [[Republic Plaza, Singapore|Republic Plaza]] have also replaced the older buildings.<ref name="100 historic places"/> The three tallest buildings in Singapore were located on Raffles Place the until the construction of [[Tanjong Pagar Centre]] in 2016.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/tanjong-pagar-centre-set-to-be-tallest-building-at-290m |title=Tanjong Pagar Centre set to be tallest building at 290m |date=May 3, 2013 |author=Melissa Tan |work=The Straits Times }}</ref>
==Notable buildings== Several key buildings are located in Raffles Place, including [[UOB Plaza]], [[One Raffles Place]], [[Republic Plaza, Singapore|Republic Plaza]], and [[OCBC Centre]]. [[The Fullerton Hotel Singapore]], a hotel at the renovated old General Post Office building, the famous tourist icon the [[Merlion]], and an ultra modern [[durian]] shaped Art Centre [[Esplanade - Theatres on the Bay|Esplanade Theatre]] are located nearby. The [[stock exchange]] of Singapore - the [[Singapore Exchange]] - is also located in the vicinity. Several key administrative buildings in Singapore, such as the [[Parliament House, Singapore|Parliament House]], the [[Supreme Court of Singapore|Supreme Court]] and [[City Hall, Singapore|City Hall]] are located north across the river, but are technically not part of Raffles Place. [[File:Raffles Place MRT Interchange Station Entrance 3, Dec 05.JPG|thumb|right|173px|Entrance to Raffles Place MRT Station.]]
==Transportation== The underground [[Mass Rapid Transit (Singapore)|Mass Rapid Transit]] station, the [[Raffles Place MRT Station]], lies directly underneath the centre of Raffles Place, and is one of the primary public transport links for Raffles Place into [[Transport in Singapore|Singapore's transport system]]. [[Bus]] services also run along Raffles Place.
